    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "I read a couple of discussions and not sure if this decision is already made, but it seems like a good idea to automatically start insert mode when entering a :terminal because it will be more natural just like when you switch to an outside terminal.\n",
    "closed_at": "2015-06-10T03:00:04Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "What would happen if there were 5 terminal windows in a horizontal split and I wanted to switch between the one on the far left to the one in the middle? Wouldn't that mean I'd have to do\n\n```\n<C-\\><C-n>\n<C-w>l\n<C-\\><C-n>\n<C-w>l\n```\n\ninstead of what's currently done:\n\n```\n<C-\\><C-n>\n<C-w>l\n<C-w>l\n```\n\nI know you can do `2<C-w>l` in the first example, but I still think it would be annoying to make nvim so unforgiving if users forgot to prepend a count.\nBesides that, I think this would make `:terminal`s even more different from regular buffers (there's already a few, see #2570).\n",
